const littleFlowers = [
  { day:1, chapter:"Chapter 1", title:"How Francis Gathered His First Companions", passage:"In the beginning, Francis — a young man of Assisi, newly converted from a life of wealth and revelry — was given by God the grace to draw others to the path of poverty and joy. The first to follow was Brother Bernard, a wealthy and respected citizen who, upon hearing Francis preach, sold all that he had and gave it to the poor. Together they opened the Gospels three times, and each time the book fell open to passages about renouncing possessions. 'This is our life and our rule,' said Francis.", reflection:"What would it take for you to 'open the book' and let something larger than yourself guide your next step?", keyTheme:"Vocation & Surrender" },
  { day:2, chapter:"Chapter 2", title:"Brother Bernard's Perfect Humility", passage:"Brother Bernard, who was the first companion, attained such holiness that Francis held him in great reverence. One day Francis said: 'I tell you, Brother Bernard has been given some of the greatest graces in the world. He has been established in such virtue that his soul, like a swallow, soars to the heights of heaven, and I am not worthy to serve so holy a friar.' Bernard's humility was so deep that he sought always the lowest place, the hardest task, the least recognition — and in this lowliness, found perfect freedom.", reflection:"Where in your life might 'seeking the lowest place' actually free you from anxiety or competition?", keyTheme:"Humility & Freedom" },
  { day:3, chapter:"Chapter 3", title:"How Francis, Doubting, Was Reassured by Brother Bernard", passage:"There came a time when Francis was seized by doubt and heaviness. He wondered whether he should spend his life only in prayer, or whether he should also preach. He feared to make the wrong choice. So he sent word to Brother Sylvester, who lived in prayer on a mountain, and to Sister Clare, asking them both to pray for guidance. Both returned the same answer: 'God wills that Francis should go forth and preach, for he was not called for himself alone but for the salvation of others.' And Francis rose up immediately, burning with the Spirit, and went forth.", reflection:"When you face a crossroads, who do you trust to help you discern? Do you have your own 'Sylvester and Clare'?", keyTheme:"Discernment & Community" },
  { day:4, chapter:"Chapter 4", title:"How Brother Angelo Guarded the Gate", passage:"When the brothers grew in number, Francis appointed Brother Angelo as gatekeeper of the friary at the Portiuncula. His instruction was simple: when anyone comes, receive them with such kindness that they know immediately they are welcome. If a robber comes, give him bread. If a sinner comes, meet him with joy. Every person at the gate is Christ arriving in disguise. Brother Angelo kept this charge with such faithfulness that the fame of the brothers' hospitality spread through all of Umbria.", reflection:"Who shows up at the 'gate' of your daily life? How do you receive them — with warmth, or with guardedness?", keyTheme:"Hospitality & Welcome" },
  { day:5, chapter:"Chapter 5", title:"The Perfect Joy of Francis", passage:"One winter day, walking with Brother Leo from Perugia to the Portiuncula through bitter cold, Francis called out: 'Brother Leo, even if our brothers gave perfect example of holiness to the whole world, write that this is not perfect joy.' He continued naming every great achievement — and denying each was perfect joy. Finally Leo asked, 'Father, what then IS perfect joy?' Francis answered: 'If, when we arrive frozen and hungry, the gatekeeper drives us away, beats us, and throws us into the snow, and we bear it patiently and with gladness, thinking of Christ's sufferings — THAT is perfect joy. For above all graces, the greatest gift is to conquer oneself and willingly suffer for the love of Christ.'", reflection:"This is one of the most challenging passages in all of Franciscan literature. Where do you find joy in difficulty — not masochism, but genuine freedom from needing things to go your way?", keyTheme:"Joy in Suffering" },
  { day:6, chapter:"Chapter 6", title:"How Francis Blessed Brother Leo", passage:"Brother Leo, the close companion and confessor of Francis, was once troubled by a terrible spiritual darkness. He could not pray, could not feel God's presence, and felt unworthy of the brothers' company. Francis, perceiving his distress, wrote him a small parchment with a blessing: 'The Lord bless you and keep you. May the Lord show His face to you and have mercy. May the Lord turn His countenance to you and give you peace. Brother Leo, may the Lord bless you.' Leo carried this parchment with him for the rest of his life. It still survives today in the Basilica of Assisi.", reflection:"When has a simple word of blessing — from a friend, a mentor, a stranger — carried you through a dark time?", keyTheme:"Blessing & Friendship" },
  { day:7, chapter:"Chapter 7", title:"Francis and the Wolf of Gubbio", passage:"The town of Gubbio was terrorized by a great wolf that devoured animals and even attacked people. The townspeople were afraid to leave the gates. Francis, moved by compassion for both the people and the wolf, went out alone to meet the creature. When the wolf charged, Francis made the sign of the cross and said: 'Come here, Brother Wolf. In the name of Christ, I command you to do no harm.' The wolf closed its mouth, lay at Francis's feet, and placed its paw in his hand. Francis brokered a peace: the town would feed the wolf, and the wolf would harm no one. The wolf lived peacefully among them for two years until its death, and the whole town mourned.", reflection:"What 'wolves' — fears, conflicts, adversaries — might be tamed not by force, but by compassion and understanding?", keyTheme:"Peace & Reconciliation" },
  { day:8, chapter:"Chapter 8", title:"How Francis Taught by Walking", passage:"A young friar once asked Francis: 'Father, will you take me with you to preach in the town today?' Francis agreed. They walked together through the streets of Assisi — past the market, through the square, by the church, along the walls — greeting people as they went, helping a woman carry her burden, stopping to speak kindly to a beggar, pausing to admire the beauty of a garden. When they returned to the friary, the young brother said: 'But Father, when shall we begin to preach?' Francis smiled and said: 'We have been preaching the whole time. Every step we took, every person we greeted — that was the sermon.'", reflection:"If your daily actions were your only 'sermon,' what would people learn about what you believe?", keyTheme:"Witness & Action" },
  { day:9, chapter:"Chapter 9", title:"The Sermon to the Birds", passage:"Near Bevagna, Francis saw a great multitude of birds gathered in the trees and fields — doves, crows, jackdaws, and many others. Seized by the Spirit, he ran toward them and began to preach: 'My sisters the birds, you ought to praise your Creator greatly, for He has given you feathers to clothe you, wings to fly, and everything you need. He has made you noble among creatures, and given you the pure air for your home.' The birds stretched their necks, spread their wings, and gazed at Francis. Not one flew away until he gave them his blessing. From that day, Francis always preached to animals and even to flowers, inviting them to praise their Creator.", reflection:"When was the last time you were truly present to the natural world — not just passing through it, but speaking to it, listening to it?", keyTheme:"Creation & Wonder" },
  { day:10, chapter:"Chapter 10", title:"The Stigmata on La Verna", passage:"Two years before his death, Francis withdrew to Mount La Verna for forty days of fasting and prayer. There, in deep contemplation, he was visited by a Seraph — a six-winged angel bearing the image of the Crucified Christ. When the vision departed, the marks of the nails appeared in Francis's hands and feet, and a wound as of a lance in his side. Francis had become so united with Christ in love that he bore in his body the very marks of the Passion. He tried to hide the wounds, but the brothers saw. Francis lived two more years in joy and suffering, preaching and blessing, until Sister Death came for him on October 3, 1226.", reflection:"You don't need stigmata to be marked by love. What has your love for others — or for God — cost you? What has it given you?", keyTheme:"Union & Transformation" },
];

